<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-143-206  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 143 206.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  March 27 1989 n410 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM mainframes scarce until fall.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>DePompa, Barbara.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM will be unable to meet demands for mainframes until the 3rdqtr of 1989 because of a lack of logic chips, and customers mayturn elsewhere to have their needs met.andP;  Prices on many productshave been cut 5 percent to offset the industry-wide downturn indemand for computers.andP;  Many cost-cutting measures have been putinto effect since 1985, including a reduction in personnel, animproved product development cycle, and the sale of assets whichwere not producing adequate returns.andP;  Such cuts in cost mean thata revenue growth as small as 6 percent in 1989 will still allowIBM to realize profits.andP;  Overseas growth is expected to be high.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (forecasts).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     SupplyMainframe ComputersForecastingPerformanceMarket AnalysisIndustry AnalysisCost Reduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>